photo.title: The pilgrimage to Stonehenge

photo.description: In January I posted a picture of the Matterhorn and explained that it had been a lifelong dream of mine to see it. See it I did, and I enjoyed it so much. But before my dream of seeing the Matterhorn I longed to see Stonehenge. Maybe it is the Sci-fi fan in me, but something about the mystery of the place has always held my imagination. But when it came to Stonehenge I never really contemplated making my vision of it a reality. I had heard that it was far outside of London. It was a long, boring trip to get there, and aside from ancient rocks, there was nothing else to see. (Plus there is the fact that I visited London once in college and never really expected to make it back. There are, after all, many other great places to see in the world. And I didn't expect to spend my time going back to a big city I had already visited. I'm from San Francisco and LA, who needs another big city! Well, it was a pretty long trip outside of London. And there really wasn't much around the ancient rocks. But it was totally worth it. I went out there with my wife, and our dear friends the Halversons (beachbumhal) . We kept each other company on the train ride and then enjoyed photographing this monument from every angle. I took so many shots because, once again, I didn't want to leave without a great shot. I must have taken a dozen of this exact same shot! Did I say it was worth it? Yes, it was worth it. I would have loved to walk up and touch it, but I guess if everyone did that then people would keep chipping chunks out of the rocks and there would be nothing left to marvel at. Ahhh...I never would have guess I would have so many fulfilling events in my life!

photo.description: I'm looking for some help. I really, really like the shots where the colors are washed out. They usually have a bright, over exposed center that dissipates towards the edges of the image. As the highlights fall off, the tones remain a soft, muted color. I really like those shots. I love how they work with portraits. Though, soft and muted, the colors retain a distinctness and vibrance. Anyone know how to do those shots? Is it a layer that photoshop can apply? Is there a photographic technique I need to learn? I'll try to find a shot and link it here as an example. Here, I found one: www.flickr.com/photos/crustydolphin/3603517865/page2/?add... Thanks for any advice you can offer!
